rmk: Coal tit call ... not filtered ... parabolic ...

An April recording from a moving, calling Coal Tit that was presumably vocalising either to advertise territorial rights or to attract (or maintain vocal contact with) a mate. I assume the bird was male. This individual switches from a burst consisting of one syllable (examples at beginning, at 0:06, 0:15 and 0:21) to another burst of two syllables (examples at 0:10, 0:18 and 0:24). The recording was made within mixed, mainly deciduous woodland (many Beech) where Coal Tit is a common breeding bird.

Coal Tit delivering standard binary calls but in this sequence three variations are included. Typical is the way the singer utters a series of identical couplets, then switches to another - but may revert to the first in the series too.  Hence, after the first variation on a theme (over the first three seconds), the theme changes at 0:04. Later in the clip, the bird revisits the first in the sequence [that is, from 0:01] and reuses this motif again from 0:16. This is typical and a caller may spend over a minute broadcasting one type of couplet before repeating another 'that was made earlier'.
